A copy constructor is a special constructor in C++ used to create a new object as a copy of an existing object.

ClassName(const ClassName &obj);

const ClassName &obj → Pass by reference to avoid infinite recursion.

If you don’t define one, C++ provides a default copy constructor (shallow copy).

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class MyClass {
public:
    int x;
    MyClass(int val) : x(val) {}

    // Copy constructor
    MyClass(const MyClass &obj) {
        x = obj.x;
        cout << "Copy constructor called\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    MyClass a(10);
    MyClass b = a; // Copy constructor called
    cout << b.x << endl; // 10
}

✅ Used when:

Passing objects by value

Returning objects by value

Explicitly creating a copy
